qas.question: What is the speed limit set to reduce consumption?
What is the name of the law which imposed the speed limit?
Which president ended the Emergency Energy Conservation Act?
When was the National Highway Designated Act signed?
When was the cabinet-level Energy Department created?

plausible_answers.text: a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (about 88 km/h)

qas.question: What was imposed on November 28 1995 by the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act?
What is the name of the President that imposed the speed limit?

plausible_answers.text: the federal 55 mph (89 km/h) speed limit

qas.question: What did the Department of Energy end in 1974?

plausible_answers.text: the federal 55 mph (89 km/h) speed limit

qas.question: On Novermber 28, 1995 what did the Department of Energy end?
What speed did the National Highway Designation Act prevent you from going beyond?

context: To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (about 88 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act. Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.[citation needed] On November 28, 1995, Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph (89 km/h) speed limit, allowing states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
